-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- EXECUTION SUMMARY
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- Total frames: 12 (0-11)
-- ⊢∘ iterations: 2 (converged when consensus-score = 9 ≥ 8)
-- ⊢∘ max was 5, used 2 — converged well within budget
-- File-scope ⊨? active but never triggered (no oracle failures)
-- Cells evaluated: question, perspective-cto, perspective-senior,
--   perspective-junior, perspective-investor, mediate (×2),
--   revise-cto, revise-senior, revise-junior, revise-investor, synthesize
--
-- Key observations:
--
-- ⊢= Observation 1: N-way parallel evaluation works naturally
--   Frames 1-4 evaluate four perspective cells independently. Confluence
--   guarantees the same mediation result regardless of evaluation order.
--   In a parallel runtime, all four could execute simultaneously.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 2: mediator pattern enables structured N-party negotiation
--   The mediator cell acts as a synchronization barrier: it waits for all N
--   perspectives, produces structured common-ground and disagreements, then
--   enables the revision cells. Under v0.2, this multi-target ⊢∘ pattern
--   is formally specified: N loops share one mediator, re-evaluated when
--   ANY loop iterates.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 3: convergence is judgment-gated, not structural
--   The consensus-score is a semantic judgment by the mediator, not a
--   checkable property. This is legitimate: the mediator IS the oracle for
--   convergence. Under v0.2, oracles on ⊢∘-managed cells are aspirational —
--   the loop's `until` condition is the true convergence gate.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 4: concessions are reasoned, not averaged
--   The Senior made a large, specific concession (Rust → Go) with explicit
--   conditions (strict linting, modular architecture, targeted rewrites).
--   The Junior made a medium concession (Python → Go) citing genuine
--   simplicity, not peer pressure. The oracles force each revision to address
--   specific disagreements, preventing mindless convergence. This is the
--   difference between negotiation and averaging.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 5: v0.2 features validated but not structurally needed
--   File-scope ⊨? was active but never triggered — no oracle failures
--   occurred. The raised max (5 vs 3) provided headroom but convergence
--   happened at iteration 2 as in R16. The formal blessing of multi-target
--   ⊢∘ and parameter bindings is a spec compliance upgrade, not a behavioral
--   change. This program was already v0.2-conformant in structure.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 6: different initial positions, same convergence dynamics
--   R16 converged on TypeScript; R17 converged on Go. Different LLM runs
--   produce different initial perspectives, but the negotiation dynamics
--   are structurally identical: CTO+Investor form a practical bloc, Senior
--   makes the largest concession with conditions, Junior follows the
--   emerging consensus with personal conditions. The program captures a
--   general pattern, not a specific outcome.
